{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Meena Keshwar Kamal | honorific_suffix = | native_name = مینا کشور کمال | native_name_lang = | image = Meena_founder_of_RAWA_speaking_in_1982.jpg | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = Meena Keshwar Kamal, 1982 | birth_date = 27 February 1956 | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1987|02|04|1956|02|27}} <!-- (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = [[Quetta]], [[Pakistan]] | death_cause = [[Assassination|Assassinated]] for her political activities | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | nationality = [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] | citizenship = | education = [[Kabul University]] | alma_mater = | occupation = [[Revolutionary]] [[political activist]], [[Feminism|Feminist]], [[Women's rights]] [[activist]] | years_active = 1977—1987 | employer = | organization = Founder of [[Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan]] (RAWA) | agent = | known_for = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | spouse = [[Faiz Ahmad]] (1976-1986) | callsign = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }} '''Meena Keshwar Kamal''' ([[Pashto language|Pashto]]/{{lang-fa|مینا کشور کمال}}; February 27, 1956 – February 4, 1987), commonly known as '''Meena''', was an [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] [[revolutionary]] [[political activist]], [[feminism|feminist]], [[women's rights]] [[activist]] and founder of [[Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan]] (RAWA), who was [[Assassination|assassinated]] in 1987.
==Biography== [[File:RAWA logo.png|thumb|Logo of the [[Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan]] (RAWA)]] In 1977, when she was a student at [[Kabul University]],<ref name="guardian.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/apr/30/afghanistan-women-feminists-burqa|title=Afghan feminists fighting from under the burqa|author=Jon Boone|work=the Guardian|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> she founded [[Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan]] ([[RAWA]]), an organization formed to promote equality and education for women and continues to "give voice to the deprived and silenced women of Afghanistan". Even after the [[Saur Revolution]] there was no vast changes of women's deprivation in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Afgan Narimukti Andoloner Agnishika (Bengali)|last=Seisab Shahidera|first=Biswas, P|publisher=Atirikto Publication|year=2014|isbn=978-81-928741-0-4|location=Kolkata|pages=44, 45}}</ref> In 1979 she campaigned against [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|DRA]], and organized meetings in schools to mobilize support against it, and in 1981, she launched a [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] feminist [[magazine]], ''Payam-e-Zan'' (Women's Message).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pz.rawa.org|title=پیام زن، نشریه جمعیت انقلابی زنان افغانستان - راوا|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref><ref name="Chavis2011">{{cite book|author=Melody Ermachild Chavis|title=Meena: Heroine Of Afghanistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RyJEynFyznkC&pg=PT1|date=30 September 2011|publisher=Transworld|isbn=978-1-4464-8846-1|pages=1–}}</ref><ref name="Gioseffi2003">{{cite book|last=Gioseffi|first=Daniela|authorlink=Daniela Gioseffi|title=Women on War: An International Anthology of Women's Writings from Antiquity to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZH2FtB14fcEC&pg=PA283|year=2003|publisher=Feminist Press at CUNY|isbn=978-1-55861-409-3|page=283}}</ref> She also founded Watan Schools to aid [[Afghan refugees|refugee]] children and their mothers, offering both [[hospital]]ization and the teaching of practical skills.<ref name="Gioseffi2003"/><ref>[http://laconneau.com/NewsletterNovember2009.html Brave Women in a War-Torn World: RAWA and Afghanistan]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
At the end of 1981, by invitation of the French Government Meena represented the Afghan resistance movement at the [[French Socialist Party]] Congress. The [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] delegation at the Congress, headed by [[Boris Ponamaryev]], left the hall as participants cheered when Meena started waving a victory sign.<ref name="rawa.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.rawa.org/meena.html|title=Biography of Martyred Meena, RAWA's founding leader|publisher=RAWA |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>{{Primary inline|date=November 2015}}
<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:Meena-1.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Meena waving a victory sign in the French Socialist Party Congress in 1981]] --> == Personal life == Kamal was married to [[Afghanistan Liberation Organization]] leader [[Faiz Ahmad]],<ref>[[Brodsky, Anne E.]] ''With all our strength : the Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan''. [[New York City]]: [[Routledge]], 2003. p. 54</ref> who was murdered by agents of [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] on November 12, 1986.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110710160918/http://web.e-ariana.com/ariana/eariana.nsf/allDocs/AC9DD311C800E73C87256CCF005E323F?OpenDocument Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, CIA Op and Homicidal Thug]</ref><ref>[http://www.womeninwar.org/CMann_afghanwomanhood.pdf Models and Realities of Afghan Womanhood: A Retrospective and Prospects] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313114943/http://www.womeninwar.org/CMann_afghanwomanhood.pdf |date=2012-03-13 }}</ref> They had three children, whose whereabouts are unknown.
==Assassination== Kamal was [[Assassination|assassinated]] in [[Quetta]], [[Pakistan]] on February 4, 1987. Reports vary as to who the assassins were, but are believed to have been agents of the Afghan Intelligence Service [[KHAD]], the Afghan [[secret police]], or of fundamentalist [[Mujahideen]] leader [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]].<ref name="guardian.co.uk" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1973184.stm|title=BBC News - SOUTH ASIA - Afghan activist's killers hanged|publisher=|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>
== Legacy == In a special issue of the [[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]] on November 13, 2006, included Meena among "60 Asian Heroes" and wrote that "Although she was only 30 when she died, Meena had already planted the seeds of an Afghan women's rights movement based on the power of knowledge." <ref>[http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/in_meena.html TIME Magazine | 60 Years of Asian Heroes: Meena] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112202432/http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/in_meena.html |date=January 12, 2007 }}</ref>
RAWA says of her "Meena gave 12 years of her short but brilliant life to struggle for her homeland and her people. She had a strong belief that despite the darkness of illiteracy, ignorance of fundamentalism, and corruption and decadence of sell outs imposed on our women under the name of freedom and equality, finally that half of population will be awaken and cross the path towards freedom, democracy and women's rights. The enemy was rightly shivering with fear by the love and respect that Meena was creating within the hearts of our people. They knew that within the fire of her fights all the enemies of freedom, democracy and women would be turned to ashes."<ref name="rawa.org"/>{{Primary inline|date=November 2015}}
An enduring quote from Meena states:<ref name="Gioseffi2003"/><ref name="Orr2011">{{cite book|author=Tamra Orr|title=We Visit Afghanistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bLyXBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA36|date=15 September 2011|publisher=Mitchell Lane Publishers, Incorporated|isbn=978-1-61228-102-5|page=36}}</ref> {{cquote| Afghan women are like sleeping lions, when awoken, they can play a wonderful role in any social revolution.}}
